\par \pard\plain \s2\ql\widctlpar\sb240\sa120\keepn\ltrpar\b\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\loch\f5\fs32\sl240\slmult1\ql\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb240\sa120\keepn{\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs32
2  Introduction}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb60\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
Rice is the most rapidly growing staple food in Africa and although rice production is steadily increasing, the consumption is still out-pacing the production. For example, by 2009 37 per cent of the rice consumed in Africa was imported. To reduce its reliance on imports and dependency on global markets Africa\u8217\'92s rice production needs to increase further [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Seck2013 \\h }{\fldrslt Seck2013}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
]. Current average yield levels in Africa range from about 1 t ha}{{\*\updnprop10000}\up8\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20
-1}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
 in upland ecologies to 1.5 to 2 t ha}{{\*\updnprop10000}\up8\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20
-1}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
 in rainfed lowland ecologies with the irrigated lowland ecologies having the highest yields of 3.0 to 4.0 t ha}{{\*\updnprop10000}\up8\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20
-1}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
 [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Diagne2013 \\h }{\fldrslt Diagne2013}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
]. Rice yields in African farmers fields are low due to a combination of abiotic and biotic stresses that constrain them. Farmers can significantly reduce the yield gaps with improved field, water and crop management, and weed control [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Saito2013 \\h }{\fldrslt Saito2013}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
].}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
Apart from weeds, pests and diseases also are major biotic stresses that can cause significant reductions in rice yields. Two important diseases in rice are leaf blast (LB) }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
Magnaporthe oryzae}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
 and bacterial blight (BB) }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
Xanthomonas oryzae}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
 pv. }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
oryzae}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
 [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Verdier2012 \\h }{\fldrslt Verdier2012}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
]. Because infectious plant disease occurs as an interaction of a favorable environment, a susceptible host and a competent pathogen [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Madden2007 \\h }{\fldrslt Madden2007}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
], weather conditions impact both the occurrence and gravity of plant disease. Climate change is likely to affect plant disease [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Anderson2004 \\h }{\fldrslt Anderson2004}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
, }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Coakley1999 \\h }{\fldrslt Coakley1999}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
, }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Garrett2006 \\h }{\fldrslt Garrett2006}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
] and several others have expressed interest in changes to plant disease as a result of climate change [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Chakraborty2011 \\h }{\fldrslt Chakraborty2011}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
, }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Juroszek2011 \\h }{\fldrslt Juroszek2011}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
, }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Luck2011 \\h }{\fldrslt Luck2011}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
, }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Pautasso2010 \\h }{\fldrslt Pautasso2010}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
, }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Savary2011 \\h }{\fldrslt Savary2011}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
, }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Sutherst2011 \\h }{\fldrslt Sutherst2011}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
]. Moreover, intensification of rice production, which was witnessed in Sub-Saharan Africa since the food crisis of 2008 [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Saito2013 \\h }{\fldrslt Saito2013}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
], may lead to an increased yield loss due to the blast, thus reducing the benefits that were created [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Sere2013 \\h }{\fldrslt Sere2013}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
]. Increases in disease incidence and severity may deter farmers from investing in intensification measures because of risks related to yield losses or even total crop failure. To the authors\u8217\'92 knowledge, the impact of climate change on leaf blast and bacterial blight diseases of rice in Africa has not yet been investigated.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
Efforts to link plant disease models with a geographic information system (GIS) to assess the impact of plant diseases spatially include Hijmans2000, which mapped the global number of pesticide applications necessary to control potato late blight using contemporary weather data. While Sparks2014 used a meta-model to generate map estimates of changes in global potato late blight due to climate change. Savary2012 developed a GIS-linked model, EPIRICE, capable of simulating several important diseases of rice, including leaf blast and bacterial blight amongst others.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
The objective of the study was to quantify the impact of climate change as forecast by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) on rice yield loss as result of BB and LB. To carry out this study, we linked two previously unlinked, existing models, EPIRICE and RICEPEST [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Willocquet2000 \\h }{\fldrslt Willocquet2000}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
, }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Willocquet2002 \\h }{\fldrslt Willocquet2002}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
], and we applied them using spatially and temporally downscaled climate change data to generate predictions on changes in plant disease impact due to climate change in Tanzania.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
Rice accounts for five percent of the total value of agricultural production in Tanzania and is the seventh most important agricultural crop with steadily increasing production over the last decade. However, rice yields in Tanzania remain significantly lower than in neighboring countries [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Barreiro_Hurle2012 \\h }{\fldrslt Barreiro\\s\\do6(H)urle2012}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
].}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
The linkage of EPIRICE with RICEPEST gives two advantages. First, RICEPEST has been used to estimate yield losses due to diseases and other pest injuries in rice in varying production situations with current weather and climate conditions. However, as plant diseases are affected by weather, the linkage with EPIRICE allows us to model the effects of climate change on both the rice crop and on the diseases while using the same weather data inputs. Second, the spatial nature of EPIRICE outputs enabled us to use RICEPEST in a GIS. Until now RICEPEST yield loss estimates have not been linked to a GIS. Linking RICEPEST with a GIS allowed us to map yield losses for the whole country of Tanzania, rather than just point based predictions of yield losses.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
This paper will continue with a justification for the study area, followed by descriptions of the EPIRICE and RICEPEST models. We will then elaborate the framework for assessing rice yield losses under climate change that links both models. The procedure for generating daily weather inputs from the downscaled climate scenarios is outlined followed by the choice of production situations. Next the results are presented, followed by a discussion and finally conclusions.}
