\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb60\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
The loose coupling approach that we adopted for this research has proven to be useful. It allows for us to examine patterns and trends that previously we were unable to easily examine. This approach should prove useful for further work where spatial modelling of rice yield loss is desired for both current conditions and future predictions.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
Some initial difficulties in selecting the proper production situation for an area outside the original application domain of the model were experienced. Because the original PS3 was based in Faizabad, Uttar Pradesh, India, the temperatures and duration of the rice were too long to be consistent with Tanzania. Because of this, we elected to modify the model using currently available information in the model itself based on our determinations of what best matched the situation on the ground. The results of the modified RICEPEST model seem to better represent possible scenarios than the original unmodified model was able to.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
The RICEPEST model is a simple empirical crop growth model that does not account for CO}{{\*\updnprop10000}\dn12\rtlch \ltrch\loch
2}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
 concentration changes and increases yield as temperature increases, though the temperature to maturity is reached sooner, which reduces net biomass accumulation. A next logical step for climate change studies could be to link EPIRICE output with a more advanced model such as ORYZA [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Oryza \\h }{\fldrslt Oryza}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
], although such a linkage will be more difficult due to the added complexity of the ORYZA model.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
Despite the predictions of climate change to reduce rice crop yields, this study predicted that the attainable yield would increase with an increase in temperatures. Since the average temperatures were below 24 C, it is likely that this would be the case as temperatures below 20 C can cause yield losses, so the increased temperatures are more optimal for tropical rice [}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BIB_Yoshida \\h }{\fldrslt Yoshida}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
].}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
Thornton2009 wrote that climate change effects are likely to be unequal across East Africa when they examined maize and bean crops. Localised adaptations to climate change will be necessary. This seems to be the case when examining the maps of change in yield losses due to BB (Figure }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
{\field{\*\fldinst  REF BMBB_Change_Map \\h }{\fldrslt ?}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
). Some areas appear to lose more than another half ton per hectare to BB than they previously have, while others appear to actually lose less to BB, gaining 0.75 t ha}{{\*\updnprop10000}\up8\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20
-1}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
 potential yield due to the reduction in the severity of BB.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\qj\widctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\dbch\af8\dbch\af9\afs24\cf0\kerning1\langfe2052\alang1081\loch\f5\fs24\lang1033\sl240\slmult1\qj\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24
The results of this study indicate that the effects of climate change on plant disease can be expected to be uneven as the environment becomes less favourable for some diseases such as LB, it becomes more favorable for others like BB. One thing that the results fail to capture is the variation in weather. Because this exercise is based on time-slice averages, what is captured here is the most likely to occur in a given year based on the climate. Weather patterns have great influence on plant diseases. However, these results should be instructive for breeders and policy makers. We should not ignore leaf blast, however these results indicate that in the future bacterial blight will be more of an issue for rice growers in Tanzania than leaf blast. This information can be useful for breeders and policy makers so breeding efforts for resistance and other mitigation methods can be put into place with this outcome in mind.}
